on":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uHntVp39EZXmU5to9X4Oeeo9-hbSRW0wx1030PwiVYY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Agu3qmQPs5Pv88pAml4pmHUg9RnQCMegIffOwAXRXqE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/F-C1pk3AuXL8ByebYziUbGVC_u9wGaps3bErasZNszA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/KiVTj9u6JP9tqI8JMmFgc3u5CPDdAWzCydoqR4T8GzY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/j0v1ShU_N_M463UnAJMu6B06yhyuIrtQOpruT-xT2f4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\r\n\r\nLiAlH $_{4}$ is a nucleophilic reducing agent, hence it will reduce $-\\mathrm{COOH}$ to $\\mathrm{CH}_{2} \\mathrm{OH},-\\mathrm{CO}$ to $-\\mathrm{CHOH}$ and $-\\mathrm{NO}_{2}$ to\r\n\r\n$\\mathrm{NH}_{2}$ but does not reduce $\\mathrm{C}=\\mathrm{C}$ linkage.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27073,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/46643070-8539-413e-b1f4-7ce8a8f76ac2-9896703_A.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 297px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/366a8342-fb77-420a-9840-f058c63905ee-9896703_B.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 407px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/35687813-df17-4da0-b775-88a803db0899-9896703_C.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 275px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8c5920bd-8325-4e6a-92b8-063a096396fe-9896703_D.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 296px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The structures of major product&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d5be738-b270-4adc-b7d0-7436cd441f53-9896703_S.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 311px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27081,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Red colouration with ceric ammonium nitrate indicates presence of alcholic group, positive iodoform test indicates presence of a secondary alcohol which can oxidise to a methyl ketone. In total 3 compounds from the given will give positive test for both the reactions:<br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/550697b7-7048-4c49-b91d-5d562bd229ef-9894611_2.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 501px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27096,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fe741bd1-8e0b-4177-8e0a-58d4edd73de6-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 109px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8f108d57-86dd-44ce-88b8-d1a7f1c4a90e-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 115px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66c856b2-5a05-4b81-8ece-fea8e98ed311-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 116px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2d5c61e4-5007-4b43-91b3-8d8cdb7cceca-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 113px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6a233f28-586e-4530-8039-d2761354080c-9709524_Solution.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 365px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27129,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Benzaldehyde &gt; Butanone &lt; Propanone &lt; Propanal","Butanone &lt; Propanone &lt; Benzaldehyde &lt; Propanal","Propanal &lt; Propanone &lt; Butanone &lt; Benzaldehyde","Benzaldehyde &lt; Propanal &lt; Propanone &lt; Butanone"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Rate</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>NAR</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#945;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>group</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>attache</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>to</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>carbonyl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>carbon</mi></math>Moreover aldehydes are more reactive than ketones.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/01a515b0-7370-4aa6-b710-f75ba8708438-image.png\" style=\"width: 436px; height: 117px;\" />&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27105,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a4b7cfdd-8343-4d0e-82af-ad21458cb08f-image.png\" style=\"width: 134px; height: 137px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/01d37b81-4b18-472b-b257-20561dc29245-image.png\" style=\"width: 236px; height: 96px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c7bf650-f659-4ec1-a621-f8d844b8878d-image.png\" style=\"width: 278px; height: 110px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/29d076d7-c510-403f-bd96-43c908ce0b86-image.png\" style=\"width: 124px; height: 173px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The haloform reaction is&nbsp;a chemical reaction where a haloform is produced by the exhaustive halogenation of a methyl ketone.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8525ef61-7ca2-4ef4-9097-6fbf4714d6f8-image.png\" style=\"width: 750px; height: 94px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27072,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Iodoform test is used to check the presence of carbonyl compounds with the structure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>CO</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> or alcohols with the structure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> in a given unknown substance. The reaction of iodine, a base and a methyl ketone gives a yellow precipitate along with an &ldquo;antiseptic&rdquo; smell.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a6ecedde-af26-4b41-a0d3-40e2fa2f7f33-WhatsAppImage2023-04-27at2.05.37PM.jpeg\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 256px;\" /></p><p>Hence, (c), (d), (e) and (f) give iodoform reaction</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27155,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>.90</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.87</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.93</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn><mo>.92</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>BM</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"The maximum number of unpaired electrons for transition metals <math><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math><br /><br />or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn></math><br /><br />Spin only magnetic moment <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt><mi>BM</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>5</mn><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></msqrt><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>35</mn></msqrt></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.92</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>BM</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27053,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/A1CCzv6CJZ8PUNZ3KRyfZcLtllxYtLDbzcq4mUVCr78.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uFNlBLd6cVWWvRf5QNJ17AyVZF4JNP2nWKbRtdxXoHE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/edBKVVxPp3EwNurAkWJO4fUUBK3JHs6bVimIZ5SSfx8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/G4o8JLy24Mdjycdsn_OcBMD1bSEaTULMGutjXNcGm5k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d4XjQlXPsjhWaoZ8VpF8_wX-JGedPoRCjHXk5XaJt3Q.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27078,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9cfb7609-ccde-4cdf-a3a8-1c1331db02ee-9895817.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 122px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1eb73445-9ea9-4a31-add2-9b08484cbd5b-9895817_B.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 122px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1203755a-2d0c-413c-a335-eaef317c16d0-9895817_C.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 122px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/78727f3b-af14-4bc9-b906-94fff91a9717-9895817_D.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 97px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Aromatic aldehydes do not respond&nbsp;Fehling&#39;s test.&nbsp;(A), (B), (C) are aromatic aldehydes.</p><p>If&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math>&nbsp;attached with carbon atom give blood red with sodium nitroprusside gives a blood red colour but not prussian blue.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27090,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0dc27cfe-8f6c-4279-b31c-2f399088fd16-image.png\" style=\"width: 193px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c600f29e-0a40-4510-96e0-ff39b73ac9f3-image.png\" style=\"width: 183px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/74497835-2f6e-4d0a-a7c1-9ea1d9ae8beb-image.png\" style=\"width: 199px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4fe711e8-058f-4027-933b-54bd55787528-image.png\" style=\"width: 211px; height: 100px;\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>This reaction is an example of aldol reaction. The product formation is shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/205d5ee2-5af2-4eba-a9fb-237dd481c2c9-cc784751-a844-4dca-8344-29b88e264ab9-image.png\" style=\"width: 612px; height: 329px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27056,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2xWp7z9IPcbjOoEt5OASgD6bMLM6Ec93VDDHdyKOhxk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27132,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f5309140-778f-4e29-8908-17cf027c27b1-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 82px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0c299e5c-7181-446d-b5c7-f0e0395c5201-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 87px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c4692c5a-1be7-4b30-bc70-a482980e703f-image.png\" style=\"width: 134px; height: 83px;\" />&nbsp;","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bc16f9ff-8214-46f8-b306-ddeb6b6e8943-image.png\" style=\"width: 179px; height: 89px;\" />&nbsp;"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e222b351-8eba-4759-9812-71d66ba83caf-image.png\" style=\"width: 544px; height: 340px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HBr</mi></math>&nbsp;attacks on given molecule and provides product in which&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi></math>&nbsp;group is attached at two sites (one is substitution and another is addition on alkene ) and it is followed by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;elimination and provides alkene which gives aldehyde on ozonolysis.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (02 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27062,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><b>Semicarbazide</b> is the chemical compound with the formula <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>OC</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>)</mo><mo>(</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>)</mo></math>. It is a water-soluble white solid. It is a derivative of urea.</p><p>Acetaldehyde reacts with semicarbazide give acetaldehyde semicarbazone, the reaction will be</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12db933e-e21c-4366-978c-cb26003abebb.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 302px;\"/></p><p>Hence the product formed has three nitrogen atoms in it.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27040,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["acetophenone $ \\lt $ benzaldehyde $ \\lt $ p-tolualdehyde $ \\lt $ p- nitrobenzaldehyde","benzaldehyde $ \\lt $ acetophenone $ \\lt $ p- nitrobenzaldehyde $ \\lt $ p-tolualdehyde","p- nitrobenzaldehyde $ \\lt $ benzaldehyde $ \\lt $ p-tolualdehyde $ \\lt $ acetophenone","acetophenone $ \\lt $ p-tolualdehyde $ \\lt $ benzaldehyde $ \\lt $ p- nitrobenzaldehyde"],"answer":3,"solution":"Reactivity $\\propto+\\mathrm{ve}$ charge on electrophilic carbon\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/wYWNTT5ReoSdt3Rnoco1-74IFRH0SILvn8lk2zXSL9U.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27030,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["(B), (C) and (E) Only","(A) and (C) Only","(C) and (D) Only","(A), (C) and (D) Only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9P7ovVhcE6BVS446H5H4HVWjTO6dZPKi9FjZMsih9dA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27020,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false"],"answer":1,"solution":"Statement I: Cross aldol condensation between two different aldehydes produces four products only if both aldehydes have $\\alpha$-hydrogen atoms. If one aldehyde lacks $\\alpha$-hydrogen (e.g., benzaldehyde and acetaldehyde), only two products are typically formed (one self and one cross). If neither has $\\alpha$-hydrogen, no aldol condensation occurs. Thus, it does not 'always' produce four products. Statement I is false.<br><br>Statement II: Benzaldehyde is an aldehyde and acetophenone is a ketone. Aldehydes are generally more reactive than ketones towards nucleophilic addition reactions due to less steric hindrance and greater electronic deficiency of the carbonyl carbon. Therefore, semicarbazide will react faster with benzaldehyde than with acetophenone. The statement claiming it forms a product with acetophenone only is incorrect. Statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27162,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/750c7422-0e05-442b-abbb-996ce1c48f64-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 130px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/81a60774-a5d3-4cce-81bb-7b4d057bbcfb-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 98px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ed6c9975-c407-47f0-a17d-94a5a0e2a378-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 96px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f8df0ef4-f2a3-4f85-a1f8-7ee297f70c49-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 129px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>DIBAL</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> (diisobutyl aluminium hydride) reduces carboxylic acid and ester to aldehydes.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27047,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A, B and C only","C and D only","B and C only","A only"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/t1EFpVzElTH1fhMFs-rpI0b_x4vsYHQ7eyy3ErWgWsI.original.fullsize.png\"><br />also gives silver mirror test with ammonical silver nitrate.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27014,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":2,"solution":"The reaction sequence proceeds as follows:<br><br>The reagent $\\text{NaBH}_4$ is a mild reducing agent that selectively reduces the aldehyde group ($-\\text{CHO}$) to a primary alcohol ($-\\text{CH}_2\\text{OH}$). The lactam (cyclic amide) ring remains unaffected.<br><br>Heating with aqueous $\\text{NaOH}$ causes the base-catalyzed hydrolysis of the lactam ring. The amide bond breaks, forming a carboxylate salt ($-\\text{COO}^-$) and a secondary amine ($-\\text{NH}-$).<br><br>Acidification with $\\text{H}_3\\text{O}^+$ protonates the carboxylate ion to form a carboxylic acid ($-\\text{COOH}$).<br><br>The final product is an open-chain amino acid derivative with the structure $\\text{HOOC}-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{CH}_2-\\text{NH}-\\text{CH(CH}_3)-\\text{CH}_2\\text{OH}$. This matches the structure given in option (C).<br><br>Answer:","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (08 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27164,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d694d7c1-a679-4ad2-a1ab-96fd1ee2b536-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 126px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cd549a3b-15c8-42b5-a1d8-580da631d906-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 124px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d2387cb5-4238-448b-86ae-b866bb8a008e-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 166px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/16f2673d-71e4-4971-8a1d-f4d088c29723-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 168px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0a436ad7-57ac-4524-8a1c-abba7a8abd7e-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 258px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27142,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f4883c34-a70a-477d-900f-3a5aecf07f96-image.png\" style=\"width: 148px; height: 159px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d897a42-b4d1-484b-a9b3-c7423427b91f-image.png\" style=\"width: 106px; height: 146px;\" /></p>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f9e9471f-90b0-4eab-8d97-90acc32e1509-image.png\" style=\"width: 107px; height: 148px;\" />","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d8e5dfa-18bc-462c-ba43-e49f5eebe766-image.png\" style=\"width: 96px; height: 138px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math> <mrow> <mi>N</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>B</mi><msub> <mi>H</mi> <mn>4</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math> is a strong reducing agent as it can reduce carboxylic acids, aldehydes, and ketones. But it cannot reduce double bonds.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71a59363-d744-4342-905c-a44c6e685ed9-image.png\" style=\"width: 308px; height: 151px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27133,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c68b86e9-d82e-495c-8672-1501591becd2-image.png\" style=\"width: 68px; height: 65px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dbed7049-0554-4d1f-b314-686a9aa7e797-image.png\" style=\"width: 66px; height: 85px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a22d3132-d985-40ea-8598-6f5ccb781aaa-image.png\" style=\"width: 79px; height: 89px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/572536e9-8260-407f-9d99-48c7e5562af6-image.png\" style=\"width: 73px; height: 102px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The above reaction sequence is given below. In the first step, halogenation reaction is occurred then elimination reaction gives cyclohexene and reductive ozonolysis gives the dialdehyde and then aldol condensation takes place and final desired product is formed.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fc2bd8e5-de0b-42a3-a770-183d5d3d648c-image.png\" style=\"width: 723px; height: 112px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27026,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["A-IV, B-III, C-I, D-II","A-II, B-IV, C-I, D-III","A-IV, B-I, C-II, D-III","A-II, B-III, C-IV, D-I"],"answer":1,"solution":"Matching reagents with aldehyde reaction types:<br><br>A (H2, Pd-BaSO4) is the Lindlar/Rosenmund catalyst used in Rosenmund Reduction to convert acyl chlorides to aldehydes, matching with II.<br><br>B (SnCl2, HCl) is used in Stephen Reaction where nitriles are converted to aldehydes via imine intermediate, matching with IV.<br><br>C (CrO2Cl2, CS2) is Jones-like reagent used in Etard Reaction for oxidizing methyl groups on aromatic rings to aldehydes, matching with I.<br><br>D (CO, HCl, Anhyd. AlCl3) is the Gatterman-Koch Reaction which directly converts benzene to benzaldehyde using CO and AlCl3 catalyst, matching with III.<br><br>Therefore the correct matching is A-II, B-IV, C-I, D-III","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27181,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GivZ5yVlc-MVTTRvVv92BXcpPv9t_f0eDedKnLWgjX0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":27151,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Aldehydes and Ketones","question":"","options":["Tollen's reagent","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><mi>NaOH</mi></math>","Alkaline&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CrO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>/</mo><msub><mi>CS</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img height=\"78\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5261f4ad-42fb-43f1-a40f-4a70bd38af1e-image.png\" width=\"295\" /></p><p><img height=\"78\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/da217b58-6b41-41c6-bf58-92d000f5d1ff-image.png\" width=\"361\" /><br /><br />It is an iodoform reaction.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]